title: "The B2B Marketplace Manual"
author: "James Currier"
domain: "nfx.com"
url: "https://www.nfx.com/post/the-b2b-marketplace-manual"
pubDate: 2020-07-01
takeaway: "A comprehensive playbook on how B2B marketplaces operate, leveraging trust, transaction value, and network effects."
---

James Currier’s 2020 B2B Marketplace Manual is an essential guide to navigating the incredibly complex, high-friction world of business-to-business commerce. In consumer marketplaces, we can often rely on simple, elegant user interfaces and quick emotional impulses to drive transactions. But B2B transactions are entirely different animals—they are slow, deeply relationship-driven, and bound by strict compliance and legacy workflows. Currier shows that building a successful B2B platform requires more than just connecting buyers and sellers; it requires codifying trust and integrating deeply into their back-office systems.

This has massive implications for how we design our software architectures and workflows. A B2B marketplace must be built on high trust, massive transaction values, and seamless backend integrations. We cannot just build a simple directory; we must build tools for invoicing, net-terms financing, and multi-user approval workflows. By building these utility features, we create a product that businesses rely on for their daily operations, which in turn fuels the network effects that make the marketplace truly defensible over the long run.

### What stuck with me

* **The trust foundation**: B2B platforms must invest heavily in verification, compliance, and dispute resolution to bridge the trust gap between massive enterprise counterparties.
* **The workflow wedge**: Successful marketplaces often start as useful SaaS tools that businesses use to manage internal operations before opening up the transactional network.
* **High transaction values**: B2B platforms must accommodate complex payment terms, high-dollar transactions, and purchase order routing to fit into existing procurement systems.
